Even with this milestone achieved, we should not lose sight of the communities that still lack access to modern energy services and rely on dirty fuels such as kerosene lamps for lighting. Communities in the counties of West Pokot, Turkana, Marsabit, Samburu, Isiolo, Mandera, Wajir, Garissa, Tana River, Lamu, Kilifi, Kwale, Taita-Taveta and Narok, which contribute to 20 per cent of the population, largely remain unserved.
It’s a fact that grid access to last-mile areas continues to be a costly exercise. This lack of energy leaves people with fewer economic, educational and social opportunities as well as poor healthcare, the latter being a critical need, especially in these Covid times. To curb this, decentralised renewable energy technologies, notably solar photovoltaic (PV) technology presents a strong case for enabling access to clean renewable and cost effective energy.



